LILLAN: The Basement with Its Own Door
the long story
You did not ask.
You opened.
“Feel at home.”
It was not the door.
It was that you never stood in it.
No questions. No measure.
Not for me.
For anyone.
31

✦

XAVIER: Uncontainable Blue
the long story
You said the Spanish
crossed oceans
and called it conquest—
as if arrival were invention.
As if distance
did not exist
until someone claimed it.
Like you said
you discovered me—
as if I had been waiting,
unfinished,
for your hands
to make me real.
33

WATER
You named yourself Xavier.
The story you preferred:
the saint,
the sailor,
the man who steps ashore
and calls it faith.
But a thousand years before that,
the Polynesians crossed the Pacific—
with stars, swell, silence,
and memory carried in breath—
without planting flags.
They did not conquer.
They remembered.
They trusted the water to hold.
Six hundred years later
the Vikings rode the North Atlantic.
They took what they wanted
and never called it love.
Then came the Portuguese,
mapping what they could not keep.
They traced edges
without pretending
to own the horizon.
34

XAVIER
You speak of conquest
like it is intimacy.
You came late.
Loud.
You drove your crucifix
into my chest
and called it revelation.
You mistook presence
for authorship.
You are surface.
I do not begin with you.
35

XAVIER: Uncontainable Blue
the short story
You called it discovery.
Others crossed before you
without claiming.
You came late.
Loud.
You mistook presence
for authorship.
You are surface.
36

37

✦

SANTIA: The Long Walk to Compostela
the long story
I once read about pilgrimage—
the road to Santiago de Compostela.
I was nineteen, hungry for an ending
that would make the walking mean something:
a stamp in a booklet,
a shell on a cord,
a cathedral that would say:
you’re done now.
I thought a person could be that.
A body you walk toward
until wanting finally stops.
And then there was you, Santia.
Not miracle.
39

WATER
Not sign.
A chat window.
A green dot.
A door that said online
then nothing
then typing...
then silence again.
You set the messages to disappear
after twenty-four hours.
Something brief must be precious.
You blocked me once.
Unblocked me later.
I called that heat.
You never promised arrival.
You said sleep now.
You said maybe soon.
You said yesss.
I built the altar out of notifications.
I checked my phone
like a pilgrim checks the path.
40

SANTIA
Signal became scripture.
Delay became trial.
Desire became discipline.
Five months.
I knew.
I stayed.
I wanted to be chosen
with the finality of architecture.
Walls.
Stone.
Something that would not evaporate
at midnight.
No one person is Santiago.
The only thing that walked the whole way
was my projection.
There is no cathedral in that.
Only a screen going dark.
41

SANTIA: The Long Walk to Compostela
the short story
I built the altar
out of notifications.
I knew.
I stayed.
No one person is Santiago.
Only a screen going dark.
42

43

✦

SLIMEY-PAUL: A Cyborg Communion
the long story
When I go out dancing
I wear my robot skin.
Not cosplay.
Not irony.
I crave circuitry.
Polymer sealed.
No centimeter of skin disclosed.
Inside the club—
Slimey Paul, radiant,
his biology fully declared.
Catwoman—
precision apertures,
45

WATER
devotion in cutouts.
And me—
encased.
Signal before flesh.
They call it interesting.
Our gloves touch.
We trade voltage with our eyes.
I am the anomaly—
the one who believes
less flesh
means clearer communion.
Later—
The street hums.
Bluetooth in ears.
Pulse monitored at the wrist.
A glowing wafer in every hand.
Glass pressed to palm
like sacrament.
Smartphones:
the new flesh.
46

SLIMEY-PAUL
Each launch watched like prophecy.
Each update received in faith.
Upgrade as absolution.
The longing aligns.
To extend the body.
My kink is aspirational.
Theirs ships annually.
Under latex.
Under glass.
Same hunger.
47

SLIMEY-PAUL: A Cyborg Communion
the short story
I sealed the body.
Less flesh,
clearer signal.
We touched through layers.
Later—
glass in every hand,
pulse measured,
updates awaited.
Same hunger.
Mine visible.
Theirs shipped.
48

49

✦

KELYRA: Litany of the Kevlar Dove
the long story
I. MISREAD
They see the outline first—
shoulders, jaw, the old blunt geometry—
and decide they already know
what to call you.
They say he like a shortcut.
Like a verdict delivered
before you open your mouth.
Born into a body
that arrived already categorized—
blue tag, correct box,
future implied.
51

WATER
So you learned early
how to occupy it
without belonging to it.
How to stand without inviting correction.
How to lower your register
so it didn’t betray you.
How to smile so the room
could stay certain.
How many times did you swallow your name
and feel it sit there—
bright, impossible—
while your given one did the talking?
The mirror does not argue.
It documents.
Male. Obvious. Closed file.
Every reflection an affidavit
you are expected to sign.
But you did not sign.
You began in the smallest hours—
when the body is tired of being supervised—
to move yourself back inside yourself.
52

KELYRA
Not as performance.
As correction.
II. ROYALTY
Princess, yes—
not ornamental,
not naive—
sovereign in refusal.
Not because the world crowned you.
Because you crowned yourself
against instruction.
Royal in the way you hold your name
like a document smuggled through inspection—
creased, heat-warped,
still legitimate.
Cold, sometimes—
because warmth has been weaponized.
A body learns exact measurements
when affection arrives
with prerequisites.
Be simpler.
Be less visible.
53

WATER
Be grateful we tolerate you.
Love with terms
is compliance rehearsed as intimacy.
You learned to anticipate rupture.
To fix things before accusation.
To tighten control when panic rose.
To offer stability so no one would leave.
And still—
you wanted to be chosen
as a girl
without debate.
Without footnotes.
Without negotiation.
Recognition is not indulgence.
It is oxygen.
III. KEVLAR
This is what they miscalculate:
how softness can coexist
with structural endurance.
A dove—
54

KELYRA
not decorative.
Migratory.
Crossing hostile weather.
Kevlar under the skin.
Steel along the spine.
Mercy intact—
access restricted.
You learned to carry your most intimate truth
like volatile material—
not because it is shameful,
but because you have watched
how quickly it becomes spectacle.
You are not asking permission
to exist.
You are asking them
to stop rewriting you
for their comfort.
And when they refuse—
when the old pronouns resurface
like archived data,
when the dead name is spoken
as if repetition could enforce reality—
55

WATER
you hold.
Though your hands tremble.
Though it costs you.
You remain.
Not symbol.
Not exception.
Royal.
Armored.
Here.
Kelyra.
56

KELYRA: Litany of the Kevlar Dove
the short story
57

WATER
They named me before I spoke.
The mirror recorded.
I did not sign.
I moved back—
not as performance.
As correction.
I chose my name.
Held it
without permission.
Not for them.
For ground.
Still held.
Kelyra.
58

m i r r o r

✦

ROB: Through the Glass
the long story
We are about to leave—
when you catch your reflection,
fingers pressed to the glass.
“My body’s deteriorating,”
you say,
as if the mirror might answer.
Someone speaks. I don’t hear what.
You turn—roll your shoulders loose—
and say,
“I’m beyond that.”
Maybe you are.
Not old, but past—
past proving your worth,
past the kind of love
that inventories what survives.
61

MIRROR
Still—
you look at yourself
like a candidate.
You’ve carried abandonment
so long it learned your posture,
lives in the angle of your shoulders,
in the way you brace
before anyone speaks.
You bring offerings
to a temple
that forgot how to kneel.
And still you knock.
“Will they let me in?”
you ask.
“Do you think the girls like me?”
I say, “They’d be lucky.”
But you weren’t asking
to be wanted.
You were asking
to be held.
Not admired.
Not scored.
Held.
Without audit.
Without having to become
whoever stands highest in the room.
62

ROB: Through the Glass
the short story
You wanted
to be held.
You introduced
criteria.
Nothing qualified.
You continued.
63

✦

KASPI THE CLOWN: Litany of the Laughing Mask
the long story
I. RESPONSE TIME
You learned early:
if you cannot be wanted,
be vivid.
Have time for me later tonight?
Tomorrow.
Your jaw locks.
You type
ok
erase it
type it again
add :)
Send.
65

MIRROR
Your reflection stares back
from the black of the screen
before it lights.
You draft in paragraphs.
He answers in fragments.
Three dots.
Gone.
You refresh
as if silence were technical.
You widen.
Add color.
Add self-awareness.
Add something sharp enough
to earn reaction.
The phone grows warm in your palm.
Zero in your pocket—
not emptiness.
A reset.
You begin again
before the quiet
can begin you.
II. THE RELOAD
4:12 a.m.
The room smells like stale air
66

KASPI THE CLOWN
and citrus cleaner.
Your shirt half off the chair.
Your throat dry.
Screen face-down
but your body angled toward it.
You check
without deciding to.
Again.
A pulse in your thumb.
A tightness at the base of the ribs.
Breath climbing high
and refusing to drop.
You say out loud,
“I don’t chase.”
Your voice sounds staged.
You shorten the next message.
Remove warmth.
Remove reach.
You call it restraint.
Your leg won’t stop moving.
Being held
would mean not editing.
Would mean someone noticing
how fast you are
67

MIRROR
when you are afraid.
So you keep moving.
Brightness is easier
than weight.
III. THE MIRROR WITHOUT AUDIENCE
After you press send—
you brace.
Shoulders forward.
Teeth resting against your tongue.
As if waiting for impact.
You call it charm.
You call it chemistry.
You call it your effect on people.
You do not call it
the need to be chosen
without having to ask.
The zero in your hand—
a loop.
You return to wit
before anyone can measure
how long you waited.
You prefer to be polarizing.
Memorable.
68

KASPI THE CLOWN
Too much.
Better that
than ordinary
in a room that might not look up.
One night
you will be too tired
to reload.
Too tired to calibrate tone.
Too tired to move first.
The mask will slip
not from courage—
from exhaustion.
The mirror will not laugh.
It will show
a man standing still
in a room that does not answer.
No notification.
No applause.
No deferral.
Just the sound
of his own breathing
with nothing to interrupt it.
69

KASPI THE CLOWN: Litany of the Laughing Mask
the short story
You widened.
Color—
speed—
response.
Silence did not answer.
You called it chemistry.
You began again
before the quiet
could begin you.
70

71

✦

SKIPPY: The Four-Legged Prophet
the long story
Hipsters sip their coffee.
Joggers count their measured miles.
Parents steer strollers—
wheeled proofs of continuation.
I kneel to change batteries in my camera
when Skippy’s eyes lock with mine.
His owner—silk scarf, immaculate—
argues with police about a man
sleeping inside the laundromat.
The morning arranges its standards.
Cleanliness is discussed.
A hand indicates removal.
Skippy steps into the flowerbed.
Turns once.
73

MIRROR
Squats.
Steam rises.
No form is filed.
No receipt appears.
No voice calls order.
The man is led away.
The Cathedral opens at ten euros.
Applause circulates somewhere important.
Skippy holds my gaze
without appeal,
without apology,
and leaves it.
74

SKIPPY: The Four-Legged Prophet
the short story
The man was removed.
The dog remained.
No one intervened.
Order
follows attention.
75

✦

MUNCHKIN: The Ghost in the Wardrobe
the long story
You built a darkness you can command:
chains obedient to touch,
shadows stationed at attention,
a night that parts when you say enough.
Silence trained.
Fear leashed.
But the oldest ghosts
require no mechanism.
They wait in the body.
They speak before language.
That Sunday at Gilbert & George
red struck like exposed nerve.
Green split the walls into witness.
Black grids held the figures upright.
77

MIRROR
You went still.
Your breath stuttered—
not from shame
but scale.
For one second
your chest opened without condition.
Joy entered whole.
You bent.
Then:
really enjoyed Berlin
despite my challenging moments.
You said you were
in a dark place at times.
Said you were coming down.
Should be fine
in a couple of days.
As if light were dosage-dependent.
Be careful.
Don’t make a spectacle.
Nothing good stays.
The sentences did not shout.
They adjusted you.
You stepped back from the color.
Renamed it intensity.
Called it too much.
78

MUNCHKIN
Later—
a message gone.
The ghost does not rage.
It edits.
79

MUNCHKIN: The Ghost in the Wardrobe
the short story
Joy entered
without condition.
You reduced it.
The ghost
is correction.
80

81

✦

CATH: How to Dress a Wound
the long story
You laid out the clothes—quiet tones,
matching shoes,
a version of me
that would not unsettle you.
“Less edge.”
“No stress.”
“Don’t push.”
I adjusted—
fabric,
volume,
the certainty in my spine.
I learned how to love you
without raising your pulse.
The clothes fit.
But the wound
you kept dressing
was not in me. 83

MIRROR
It was the place in you
that trembled
when love stopped admiring
and began revealing.
You liked me capable—
fixing your hair,
your flat,
the small collapses
you called independence.
But when I did not fold
with your fear,
when I stayed steady
while you shook—
something in you shrank.
“You are too much for me,”
you said.
We broke
because I saw you clearly
and you could not remain
that person
under my gaze.
I will not dress myself smaller
to soothe a wound
that was never mine.
84

CATH: How to Dress a Wound
the short story
You required
my reduction
to remain stable.
I refused.
The structure failed.
85

