RICHIE GOLDFINGER: Litany for the Silent Listener
the long story
I. FLESH
I saw him once.
Unless I required him.
It was in the garden—
music dissolving into dusk,
air thick enough to slow the body.
He sat beneath a tree
(I never asked its name),
smoking without urgency,
watching people move
as if they were weather passing.
Half-naked. Salt on his collarbones.
Around his neck:
89

PEN
a golden pen
on a chain thin enough
to vanish against skin.
It caught light.
Released it.
Caught it again.
His eyes—
blue without demand.
A surface that did not seek reflection.
I read him poems.
Too fast.
Too eager.
Like a clown insisting on gravity.
He did not praise.
Did not correct.
Did not interrupt.
He stayed.
His fingers rested on the pen
as if it were listening
instead of him.
I saved his number.
“Call me Richie,” he said.
“One day I’ll take you to England.”
We never again mentioned England.
90

RICHIE GOLDFINGER
II. BREATH
I saved him as Richie Goldfinger—
because myth requires a surface.
Night after night
I sent poems.
Signals disguised as intimacy.
The blue checkmarks appeared
at 4:03 a.m.—
two small confirmations
that something
had crossed distance.
Never an answer.
Then the dreams adjusted scale.
He arrived without contour.
A charge before anatomy.
The pen at his throat
kept impossible time.
He sat on my chest
and counted my ribs
like structural beams.
Each breath entered him
and returned sharpened.
The ceiling thinned.
The room lost atmosphere.
The pen opened.
91

PEN
Not ink—
calibration.
A fine, cold line
drawn down the sternum
as if marking a fault line.
I woke gripping air.
Hands aching
from weight that was not there.
My phone held drafts
cleaner than my waking speech.
Measured.
Exact.
Is he a man?
Or a device I constructed
to bear the pressure
of being heard?
Am I sending into him—
or using him
to authorize the split?
The dreams expanded further.
Loneliness no longer fit the body.
It required orbit.
The grief was planetary—
not romantic.
92

RICHIE GOLDFINGER
A system aware
of its own failing climate.
Transmission without guarantee.
Signal without atmosphere.
III. SHADOW
I began writing with the golden pen.
It did not exist.
Yet the lines aligned.
Each morning
I sent a poem into silence.
Each night
the blue checks confirmed receipt.
Until one dawn—
while the refrigerator hummed
and my pulse misfired—
a message arrived.
From his number.
“Your ache is precise.”
No greeting.
No warmth.
Assessment.
Days reorganized around that sentence.
93

PEN
I brewed tea for him.
Paused for his approval.
Felt him near
when language tightened correctly.
My doctor prescribed pills
for anxiety.
For rumination.
For the insomnia
of excessive scale.
Small white corrections
for planetary grief.
The drafts softened.
The edge blurred.
The golden pen grew difficult to locate.
Then it was gone.
No ceremony.
No drain.
Just absence.
The nights steadied.
The blue checks stopped.
Sleep returned
like a reduced orbit.
Weeks later—
4:03 a.m.—
94

RICHIE GOLDFINGER
an unknown number.
A long poem.
Controlled.
Measured.
About isolation between signals.
About distance no body can cross.
About wanting to be read
without burning up on entry.
I did not answer.
I let it arrive.
Let it mark itself as seen.
And in that thin blue light
I understood—
The listener was never him.
It was the chamber
I built to survive my own transmission.
The pills did not cure the grief.
They thinned the atmosphere.
Now someone else writes into it.
And I—
I remain.
A surface without echo.
A planet long cooled
still receiving signals
no one remembers sending.
95

PEN
Unreadable.
Exact.
96

RICHIE GOLDFINGER: Litany for the Silent Listener
the short story
I sent.
You did not answer.
The signal held anyway.
You spoke once:
your ache is precise.
It reorganized me.
Then you were gone.
The writing stayed.
Not you.
The chamber.
I remained inside it—
sending, without reply,
and still received.
Exact.
97

✦

KAIN: The Scribe of Temporary Things
the long story
Behind the amphitheater’s roar,
where Céline Dion’s high notes scatter
like secular hymns into the afternoon,
I find Kain kneeling with his spray cans
before the city’s exposed vertebrae—
that slithering, serpent-backed concrete
we still call a wall.
“What is a city
but an altar?” he asks.
He does not look at me
when he says it.
“What is society
but a temple we build
to sacrifice to what we cannot name?
We train our priests—
99

PEN
artists, teachers—
and let our leaders draft the psalms
of progress, of good, of necessary.
But this—”
His palm rests
against the graffitied skin.
“This Wall is the real temple.
It governs the bells of this city.
It decides what survives.”
Wind moves along the concrete
like breath through a ribcage.
And if it speaks,
it does not promise mercy.
Break me.
Broken things gain surface.
Paint fumes sting—
eyes, lungs—
a raw incense.
Sssssch.
The can exhales.
Pressure released into color.
Names swallow names.
Layer upon layer.
Each tag a brief republic
declaring: I was.
No permanence.
100

KAIN
Only insistence.
I understand then
what ritual requires.
From my inner pocket
I draw the Golden Pen—
metal warm from other inscriptions,
attached to its narrow chain.
I hesitate.
Not from doubt—
but from the knowledge
that permanence can be a kind of theft.
To my right,
Richie meets my gaze
and nods once.
Witness.
I extend the Pen.
Kain takes it
as if accepting something heavier than metal.
For one suspended instant
spray, stone, breath,
and sun align.
He does not carve.
He writes over drying color.
Letters flare—
not deeper than paint,
101

PEN
not stronger than weather,
but exact.
Already fading.
Already sufficient.
Around us, Mauerpark hums—
a busker bending “My Heart Will Go On”
into something cracked and human,
tourists turning fragments of concrete
into private relics.
The Pen swings lightly
from its chain
when he returns it.
A pendulum.
Time does not stop.
The Wall does not crumble.
Berlin does not tilt.
But something accepts inscription.
And isn’t that the hunger—
not to last,
but to be received?
To press breath against stone
and feel resistance answer?
On this Sunday,
before a monument that failed
102

KAIN
and therefore multiplied,
Kain signs—
not into eternity,
but into surface.
And the surface,
for a moment,
does not refuse him.
And that is all we ever ask of the world.
103

KAIN: The Scribe of Temporary Things
the short story
Nothing holds.
Still—
we write.
Not to last.
To be received.
Surface
is enough.
104

105

✦

ANDERS: The Hand Behind These Walls
the long story
I sketched the plans—
wobbly lines on graph paper,
a boy’s geometry of what might hold.
You studied them
as if they were already load-bearing.
Never once said,
“This won’t stand.”
Your hands—creased, deliberate—
followed my crooked angles,
found weight where I had drawn only hope.
The cannon came first.
Wheel. Barrel. Axle true.
You showed me how wood could carry force
without splintering.
107

PEN
Then the horse—
oak legs jointed to move,
white paint laid in patient coats
while I learned how steady
a hand must become
to make something live.
The fort came last.
Walls thick enough for siege.
Towers too tall.
A moat we cut into stubborn earth,
stone by stone.
“Will it keep them out?” I asked.
“It’ll keep you safe,” you said.
I thought you meant the walls.
What you were building
was measurement.
Balance.
The habit of checking a line twice
before trusting it.
Not a fortress—
but a frame.
Every toy a rehearsal in gravity.
Every quiet correction
a beam set straighter than before.
You were transferring weight—
from your hands
108

ANDERS
into mine.
Now the hammer rests differently in my grip.
Heavier.
The lines still tremble—
but they meet.
When a structure holds
through weather,
I feel it first
in the wrist.
109

ANDERS: The Hand Behind These Walls
the short story
The line did not hold
until it did
under your hands.
Weight entered
before understanding.
Now—
when something stands,
I feel it
in the wrist.
110

111

✦

BETTY BEDBUG: The Unseen Companion
the long story
They said it was nothing—
no movement,
no touch.
But I know the register beneath silence.
The seam that warms
when the body surrenders.
You did not arrive with spectacle.
You arrived with accuracy.
A mouth the size of a comma
rewriting the sentence of sleep.
I answered like a man who believes
purity can be restored by force.
Boiling water.
Chemical fog.
113

PEN
Mattress flayed open
like something confessing.
I bled the bathroom white.
You did not retreat.
You refined.
Now the house stands disciplined.
Minimal.
Inspectable.
And still—
at the hour when the mind loosens its guard—
you enter.
Not violently.
Precisely.
You take what you require.
You leave almost nothing behind
except the knowledge
that something fed.
They say I lost everything—
work reduced to absence,
study dissolved,
morning light no longer neutral.
They say the problem was small.
But small things
govern empires of nerve.
I stopped asking whether you were real
114

BETTY BEDBUG
the night I understood
that absence bites harder
than any creature.
You are not my enemy.
You are the proof
that something
still
wants me.
Soft.
Anonymous.
Unmoved by dignity.
When love thinned,
when faith retracted,
when the rooms forgot my name—
you remained.
Not kind.
Not cruel.
Simply present.
And in the strict economy of presence,
that is more than most.
115

BETTY BEDBUG: The Unseen Companion
the short story
They said nothing was there.
Still—
something fed.
Not violently.
Precisely.
I tried to remove it.
It adapted.
Left almost nothing
except knowledge:
I am being taken from.
I stopped asking
116

BETTY BEDBUG
if it was real.
Absence bit harder.
You remained.
Not kind.
Not cruel.
Present.
In that measure—
more than most.
117

✦

EKO: Litany for the Ritual of Rewriting
the long story
I. WATER
I did not arrive as a person.
I arrived as a registration—
a name aligned to a box.
In water, the body does not negotiate.
Salt enters.
Breath leaves.
One summer I went under
and the surface sealed above me.
Long enough
to understand
how quickly fine becomes fiction.
119

PEN
If you cannot be safe, be legible.
If you cannot be held, be exact.
So I became quiet
in a way the system could keep.
Tell me—
what did you rename your fear
when you began wearing it
like manners?
II. MIRROR
The mirror did not reflect me.
It confirmed me.
Are you consistent?
Are you still the same file?
I practiced faces for clearance.
Smile: access.
Neutral: passage.
Laughter: stability.
I became fluent in approval.
Honesty feels holy—
but you did not yet know
the difference
between revelation
and compliance.
120

EKO
Micro-scene:
Someone asked who I was.
I offered the version
that would prevent departure.
Who benefits
when you remain interpretable?
Who calls you “too much”
only because they refuse
the labor of seeing?
III. PEN
Then the pen—
not as art.
As boundary.
I wrote my name
until it stopped being a label
and became mass.
EKO—I remain.
Not because I cannot break.
Because I return.
Staying legible
was erasing me.
I refused the story
where I am footnote to my own life—
121

PEN
where I disappear quietly
and call it maturity.
This is The Book of Names:
not archive,
but resistance.
I write them
so absence cannot pretend
it was inevitable.
Names as anchors.
Names as refusal.
Record as a form of love
that does not ask permission.
O pen—
be mercy in the hands of others,
and weight in mine.
I will not be authored
by fear.
I will not remain
legible at the cost of self.
You do not write me.
So I cannot write you.
I can only place the instrument
back in your hand.
Take it.
Write.
122

EKO: Litany for the Ritual of Rewriting
the short story
I was a registration.
In water,
the body does not negotiate.
If you cannot be safe,
be legible.
The mirror confirmed me.
Consistent.
Clear.
Approved.
Until—
a line did not match.
123

PEN
I chose it.
Not for safety.
For self.
I write
so absence
cannot call itself truth.
124

OUTSIDE THE TEMPLE OF OFFERINGS
A pale wind stirs the dust. The great doors stand open but dark.
The marble steps are cracked; faint inscriptions flicker and fail—
half-erased prayers. No music. Only wind. A distant city hum,
thinning.
KELYRA sits on the steps, shawl wrapped tight. Not guarding.
Not begging. Resting.
ROB approaches, carrying something wrapped in worn cloth. He
stops before sitting. He does not enter the temple.
ROB
I thought it would feel different.
Warmer.
But it’s just stone.
KELYRA
It was always stone.
125

CODA
ROB
I brought something.
KELYRA
You always do.
ROB
Do I know you?
KELYRA
You know the armor.
That was enough for most.
ROB
You look finished.
KELYRA
With kneeling.
ROB
It was going to be an offering.
KELYRA
To who?
ROB
Whoever keeps the ledger.
KELYRA
No one is inside.
126

OUTSIDE THE TEMPLE OF OFFERINGS
SANTIA appears briefly, scallop shell threaded on a cord. She
touches the stone, waits, then walks on.
ROB
She’s still walking.
KELYRA
Some people think arrival
is a person.
XAVIER touches the threshold. The darkness does not answer. He
withdraws.
ROB
And him?
KELYRA
He mistook silence for permission.
A faint laugh from within—KASPI, unseen. It fades when no one
responds.
ROB
I don’t know how to stop offering.
KELYRA
Then don’t.
ROB
My hands don’t know what else to do.
127

CODA
KELYRA
Let them be empty.
ROB
It feels like falling.
KELYRA
It is.
SKIPPY bounds in, lifts his leg against a pillar. The temple does
not respond.
KELYRA
There.
SKIPPY drops a gold pen at ROB’s feet.
ROB
Why would he—
KELYRA
Because you don’t need an altar.
You need a hand.
ROB picks up the pen. It rests in his palm. LILLIAN places a candle
between them and leaves.
ROB
It’s lighter than I thought.
KELYRA
128

OUTSIDE THE TEMPLE OF OFFERINGS
Yes.
ROB sets the wrapped bundle beside him. Not inside. Not opened.
ROB
What if no one writes us into anything?
KELYRA
Then we write.
ROB
We’re not myths.
KELYRA
No.
ROB
We’re just—
KELYRA
—outside.
A long pause. The light shifts—neither dusk nor dawn, but something between. The temple exhales, relieved of witness. The doors
remain open. Unentered. No offering is made. Blackout.
129